Preprocessing with Python¶

Introduction¶

Author: Kyriacos Nicolaou (kyriakosn24@gmail.com)
Updated: October 9, 2024

In this notebook, we will preprocess images from a multiplex immunofluoresence experiment to obtain the necessary components do spatial modeling of puncta patterns. The preprocessing steps include:

  1. Extracting Puncta Centroids: From the images representing the puncta structures, we aim to pinpoint their centroid coordinates to generate a list of points.

  2. Defining the cell interior: We need to obtain the contour of the domain where the puncta are located. This domain corresponds to the cytosol—the interior region of the cell excluding the nucleus.

  3. Constructing Derived Predictor Maps: We will create derived predictor maps such as binary masks, distance maps, and proximity maps based on the imaged components.

  4. Stitching data for Multiple Cells: To fit the model on multiple cells, we will geographically "stitch" the different images and point patterns into a single composite dataset.

  5. Export data : We will export the contents of these dictionaries in an appropriate format for spatial modeling in R.

The final output will be a dictionary with the following structure:

dataset

│   ├── raw

Importing Libraries¶

We will import the necessary libraries for preprocessing:

  • Pillow: For reading the raw images
  • Geopandas, rasterio, Shapely: For data export to approriate formats for R-inlabru analysis.
  • NumPy, SciPy: For numerical computations and handling arrays.
  • OpenCV, scikit-image: For image processing.
  • Matplotlib: For data visualization.

Reading Raw Images for Each Cell¶

We will collect raw image data for each cell into a dictionary. Each image has multiple channels, each representing a different cellular component:

Index Channel
0 Nucleus
1 Lipid Droplets
2 Peroxisomes
3 Mitochondria
4 Golgi Apparatus
5 Endoplasmic Reticulum (ER)
6 Nucleus

Note: there are two nucleus channels since they were used for alignment in the multiplex experiment, in our case we will neglet the channel at index 6

These raw images will be stored in our dataset dictionary

In [2]:
# List of cells to process
cell_list = ["cell1", "cell2", "cell3", "cell4", "cell5", "cell6"]

scale = 10.8557

# Initialize the dataset dictionary
dataset = {cell: {} for cell in cell_list}

for cell in cell_list:
    dataset[cell]["raw"] = dict()
    dataset[cell]["binary"] = dict()
    dataset[cell]["point patterns"] = dict()
    dataset[cell]["contours"] = dict()
    dataset[cell]["proximity"] = dict()
    dataset[cell]["distance"] = dict()
    
dataset["scale"] = 10.8557  # pixels per micrometer

# List of all channels in the images
all_channels = ["nucleus", "lipid droplets", "peroxisomes", "mitochondria", "golgi", "ER"]

# Read all images for each cell
for cell in cell_list:
    file_path = f"../data/raw/{cell}/mpx.tif"
    with PIL.Image.open(file_path) as img:
        # Iterate over each frame (channel) in the TIFF file
        for frame, channel in enumerate(all_channels):
            try:
                img.seek(frame)
                dataset[cell]["raw"][channel] = np.array(img)
            except EOFError:
                print(f"Frame {frame} not found in {file_path}")
                break

Visualization Helper Functions¶

To facilitate data exploration and visualization, we will construct two helper functions:

  • imshow(axis,image): this function plots an image in grayscale with black indicating high intensity and white indicating low intensity, the image is shown such that the origin is at the lower left corner, and the axis are adusted for the corresponding lengths, more over a scale bar of $10 \mathrm{\mu} m$ is added

  • multiplot(dataset_dictionary,cells, imagesets, imagesubsets): This function takes a dictionary in the format we showed before, meaning the first layer is the cell names, second layer are different image sets (e.g. raw,binary,distance) and last image subsets (e.g mitochondria, er), and lists for each layer cells, sets, subsets. The function will plot a multipannel figure with the images that correspond to the combinations of the elements of these lists.

In [3]:
def imshow(ax,image):
    xlength = image.shape[1]/scale
    ylength = image.shape[0]/scale
    ax.imshow(image, cmap='binary',origin = "lower",extent = (0,xlength,0,ylength))
    ax.plot([xlength-15,xlength-5],[0.05*ylength,0.05*ylength],color = "black")
    ax.text(s = r"$10\mathrm{\mu m}$",x = xlength-10, y = 0.07*ylength,horizontalalignment = "center")
    ax.set_xticks([])
    ax.set_yticks([])


def multiplot(dataset_dictionary, cells, imagesets, imagesubsets):

    combinations = list(itertools.product(cells, imagesets, imagesubsets))
    number_of_images = len(combinations)
    
    ncols = 3
    nrows = int(np.ceil(number_of_images / ncols))

    # Create subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(5, 5))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    # Plot each image
    for idx, keys in enumerate(combinations):
        cell,set,subset = keys
        ax = axes[idx]
        image = dataset_dictionary[cell][set][subset]
        imshow(ax,image)
        ax.set_title(f"{cell}/{set}/{subset}",fontsize = 8)
    # Hide any unused subplots
    for idx in range(number_of_images, nrows * ncols):
        fig.delaxes(axes[idx])
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Localizing Puncta Structures¶

We will localize puncta structures within the cells. Puncta are small, dot-like features representing cellular components like peroxisomes or lipid droplets. Accurate localization allows us to quantify puncta distribution and analyze spatial patterns.

We will use the Laplacian of Gaussian (LoG) blob detection method from skimage to detect puncta by identifying intensity differences. our image data.

In [6]:
# function to get puncta coordinates and radius
def get_blobs(image,min_sigma,max_sigma,threshold,ns):
    blobs_log = sk.feature.blob_log(image,min_sigma=min_sigma, max_sigma=max_sigma, num_sigma=ns, threshold = threshold)
    return blobs_log[:,1]/scale ,blobs_log[:,0]/scale , np.sqrt(2)*blobs_log[:,2]/scale

max_size_in_px = 10 #about 1 um 
min_size_in_px = 1 #about 0.1 um 
n_steps = 10
threshold_peroxisomes = 60
threshold_lipid = 200


for cell in cell_list:
    peroxisomes_x, peroxisomes_y, peroxisomes_r = get_blobs(dataset[cell]["raw"]["peroxisomes"]*1.0,min_size_in_px,max_size_in_px,threshold_peroxisomes, n_steps)
    dataset[cell]["point patterns"]["peroxisomes"] = np.array([peroxisomes_x, peroxisomes_y, peroxisomes_r])

    lipid_x, lipid_y, lipid_r = get_blobs(dataset[cell]["raw"]["lipid droplets"]*1.0,min_size_in_px,max_size_in_px,threshold_lipid, n_steps)
    dataset[cell]["point patterns"]["lipid droplets"] = np.array([ lipid_x, lipid_y, lipid_r])

Identifying Cell Domain and Extracting Contours¶

We will identify the cell domain and extract the contours of the cell boundary and nucleus to define spatial regions for analysis:

  1. Create Binary Masks: Generate binary masks for the cell and nucleus using thresholding techniques.
  2. Extract Contours: Use OpenCV's contour detection functions to extract cell and nucleus boundaries from the binary masks.
In [9]:
# the segmentation was essentially done before in imageJ so the non-cell pixels are set to zero for all the images

threshold = 0

for cell in cell_list:
    cells_mask = sk.morphology.closing(dataset[cell]["raw"]["nucleus"] >threshold,sk.morphology.disk(5))
    dataset[cell]["binary"]["cell"] = cells_mask

multiplot(dataset,cell_list, ["binary"],["cell"])
In [10]:
threshold = 10

for cell in cell_list:
    nucleus_mask = dataset[cell]["raw"]["nucleus"] > threshold
    nucleus_mask = sk.morphology.remove_small_holes(nucleus_mask,20)
    nucleus_mask = sk.morphology.remove_small_objects(nucleus_mask,100)
    nucleus_mask = sk.morphology.closing(nucleus_mask, sk.morphology.disk(10))
    nucleus_mask = sk.morphology.opening(nucleus_mask, sk.morphology.disk(10))
    dataset[cell]["binary"]["nucleus"] = nucleus_mask
    
multiplot(dataset,cell_list, ["binary"],["nucleus"])
In [11]:
for cell in cell_list:
    dataset[cell]["binary"]["domain"] = dataset[cell]["binary"]["cell"] & ~ dataset[cell]["binary"]["nucleus"]
multiplot(dataset,cell_list, ["binary"],["domain"])

Now we will identify the contours using cv2.findContours, and we make the contours are closed, by appending a copy of the the first coordinate set to the end of the contour coordinates

In [12]:
for cell in cell_list:
    
    cell_contour, _ = cv2.findContours(dataset[cell]["binary"]["cell"].astype(np.uint8), cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
    dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"] = cell_contour[0][:,0,:]/scale
    dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"] = np.vstack((dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"],dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"][0]))
    
    nucleus_contour, _ = cv2.findContours(dataset[cell]["binary"]["nucleus"].astype(np.uint8), cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
    dataset[cell]["contours"]["nucleus"] = nucleus_contour[0][:,0,:]/scale
    dataset[cell]["contours"]["nucleus"] = np.vstack((dataset[cell]["contours"]["nucleus"],dataset[cell]["contours"]["nucleus"][0]))

Creating Proximity Maps¶

We will generate proximity maps to analyze spatial relationships between puncta and nearby structures:

  • Mitochondria
  • Golgi Apparatus

Proximity maps will be created by dilating binary masks up to 1 micrometer and subtracting the original masks to isolate nearby regions. on.

Let's proceed to generate the proximity maps and integrate them into our dataset.

In [17]:
def create_border_mask(binary_mask, distance):
    dilated_mask = sk.morphology.binary_dilation(binary_mask, footprint=sk.morphology.disk(distance))
    border_mask = dilated_mask & ~binary_mask
    return border_mask

for cell in cell_list:
    dataset[cell]["proximity"]["mitochondria"] = create_border_mask(dataset[cell]["binary"]["mitochondria"],scale)

multiplot(dataset,cell_list, ["proximity"],["mitochondria"])
In [18]:
for cell in cell_list:
    dataset[cell]["proximity"]["golgi"] = create_border_mask(dataset[cell]["binary"]["golgi"],scale)

multiplot(dataset,cell_list, ["proximity"],["golgi"])

Creating Relative Distance Maps¶

We will generate distance maps for large cellular structures, specifically the nucleus and cell border, to capture heterogeneity in puncta distribution:

  1. Calculate Distance Maps: Compute pixel distances from the nucleus and cell border.
  2. Compute Relative Distance: Use a normalized formula:
In [19]:
for cell in cell_list:
    dataset[cell]["distance"]["nucleus"] = sp.ndimage.distance_transform_edt( ~dataset[cell]["binary"]["nucleus"])*dataset[cell]["binary"]["domain"]/scale
    dataset[cell]["distance"]["cell"] = sp.ndimage.distance_transform_edt( dataset[cell]["binary"]["cell"])*dataset[cell]["binary"]["domain"]/scale
    dataset[cell]["distance"]["fractional distance"] =  np.divide(dataset[cell]["distance"]["cell"],dataset[cell]["distance"]["nucleus"]+dataset[cell]["distance"]["cell"],out=np.zeros_like(dataset[cell]["distance"]["cell"]),
            where=dataset[cell]["distance"]["nucleus"]+dataset[cell]["distance"]["cell"]!=0)

multiplot(dataset,cell_list, ["distance"],["fractional distance"])

Stitching Data Across Multiple Cells for Spatial Analysis¶

In our spatial analysis, we aim to investigate patterns not only within individual cells but also across multiple cells. To perform spatial analysis on multiple cells collectively, we need to geographically stitch the images, contours, and point patterns from individual cells into a single, cohesive dataset. This process involves aligning the data from multiple cells into a common coordinate system, effectively combining them into a larger spatial domain.

In [20]:
def stitch(big_matrix,small_matrix,x0,y0):
    big_matrix[y0:y0+small_matrix.shape[0], x0:x0+small_matrix.shape[1]] = small_matrix
    return big_matrix

shift = dict()
shift["cell1"] = {"x": 150, "y" :150}
shift["cell2"] = {"x": 150, "y" :1150}
shift["cell3"] = {"x": 1200, "y" :1000}
shift["cell4"] = {"x": 1200, "y" :150}
shift["cell5"] = {"x": 2070, "y" :1000}
shift["cell6"] = {"x": 2000, "y" :150}

dataset["stitched"] = dict()

image_sets = ["raw","binary","proximity","distance"]

for image_set in image_sets:
    dataset["stitched"][image_set] = dict()
    for key, value in dataset["cell1"][image_set].items():
        bigger_picture = np.zeros((1700,2800),dtype = dataset[cell_list[0]][image_set][key].dtype)
        for cell in cell_list:
            bigger_picture = stitch(bigger_picture,dataset[cell][image_set][key],shift[cell]["x"],shift[cell]["y"])
        dataset["stitched"][image_set][key] = bigger_picture

dataset["stitched"]["contours"] = dict()

for cell in cell_list:
    dataset["stitched"]["contours"][cell] = dict()
    shifted_contour = dataset[cell]["contours"]["nucleus"].copy()
    shifted_contour[:,0] += shift[cell]["x"]/scale
    shifted_contour[:,1] += shift[cell]["y"]/scale
    dataset["stitched"]["contours"][cell]["nucleus"] = shifted_contour

    shifted_contour = dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"].copy()
    shifted_contour[:,0] += shift[cell]["x"]/scale
    shifted_contour[:,1] += shift[cell]["y"]/scale
    dataset["stitched"]["contours"][cell]["cell"] = shifted_contour

dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"] = dict()
dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"]["peroxisomes"] = np.zeros((3,0))
dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"]["lipid droplets"] = np.zeros((3,0))
                                             
for cell in cell_list:
    shifted_point_pattern = dataset[cell]["point patterns"]["peroxisomes"].copy()
    shifted_point_pattern[0] += shift[cell]["x"]/scale
    shifted_point_pattern[1] += shift[cell]["y"]/scale
    dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"]["peroxisomes"] = np.hstack((dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"]["peroxisomes"],shifted_point_pattern))

    shifted_point_pattern = dataset[cell]["point patterns"]["lipid droplets"].copy()
    shifted_point_pattern[0] += shift[cell]["x"]/scale
    shifted_point_pattern[1] += shift[cell]["y"]/scale
    dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"]["lipid droplets"] = np.hstack((dataset["stitched"]["point patterns"]["lipid droplets"],shifted_point_pattern))
In [21]:
def bounding_box(small_matrix,x0,y0,margin):
    width = small_matrix.shape[1]
    height = small_matrix.shape[0]
    left = x0 - margin
    right = x0 + width + margin
    bot = y0 - margin
    top = y0 + height + margin
    xs = [left,left,right,right,left]
    ys = [bot,top,top, bot,bot]
    return np.array([xs, ys])/scale

dataset["stitched"]["bounding boxes"] = dict()
for cell in cell_list:
    dataset["stitched"]["bounding boxes"][cell] =  bounding_box(dataset[cell]["raw"]["nucleus"],shift[cell]["x"],shift[cell]["y"],100)

Saving Processed Data for Further Analysis¶

With all preprocessing steps completed, we now need to save our data for future use. First, we will save the entire dataset as a Python-friendly object using pickle, which allows us to preserve the dataset's structure and quickly reload it in Python for any additional processing or analysis.

Next, we will export the different data objects into file formats compatible with the spatial analysis tools we plan to use later, such as R. By saving the data in formats that these tools can readily import, we streamline the workflow and ensure seamless integration between Python preprocessing and subsequent spatial modeling.

Steps for Saving Data*¶

  • Pickle the Dataset: Use Python's pickle module to serialize the dataset dictionary and save it tin Python.

  1. Export Data for Spa in Rtial Analysis:

    • Point Patterns:
      • Save the coordinates of the puncta (e.g., peroxisomes, lipid droplets) as CSV files or other suitable formats.
      • Include any additional attributes, such as radii or intensity values, if applicable.
    • Contours and Masks:
      • Export the contours of the cell border and nucleus, possibly as shapefiles, GeoJSON, or other spatial formats recognized by R's spatial packages.
      • Save binary masks or distance maps as image files (e.g., TIFF, PNG) or as matrices in CSV format.
    • Predictor Maps:
      • Save derived predictor maps (binary masks, proximity maps, distance maps) in formats that can be imported into R, such as raster images or matrices.
    • Metadata:
      • Include any relevant metadata, such as scaling factors or cell identifiers, in a separate file or embedded uccessfully saved to {pickle_filename}")

    p2 = shapely.geometry.Polygon(zip(dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"][:,0], dataset[cell]["contours"]["cell"][:,1]))
    domain_polygons.append(shapely.geometry.Polygon(p2.exterior.coords, [p1.exterior.coords]))
    contour_dicitonary = {'ID': [cell], 'geometry': domain_polygons}
    gdf_polygons = gpd.GeoDataFrame(contour_dicitonary)
    gdf_polygons.to_file("../data/processed/inlabru_compatible/" + cell + "/domain.geojson", driver="GeoJSON",crs=None)

def save_rast(matrix,scale,output_file):
    matrix_f = np.flipud(matrix)
    
    resolution = 1/scale  # Resolution in micrometers (assuming square cells)
    
    # Calculate the transform matrix
    transform = rasterio.transform.from_origin(0, matrix.shape[0]/scale, resolution, resolution)

    if (matrix_f.dtype).name == "bool":
        matrix_f = matrix_f.astype(np.uint8)
    
    # Create a rasterio MemoryFile object to write the raster data
    with rasterio.open(output_file, 'w', driver='GTiff', height=matrix_f.shape[0], width=matrix_f.shape[1],
                           count=1, dtype= (matrix_f.dtype).name, crs= None,
                           transform=transform) as dst:
            # Write the matrix data to the raster dataset
            dst.write(matrix_f, 1)
